name: physostigmine
Reason:
Physostigmine features several functional groups that would influence its melting point. The core structure is a tricyclic compound which provides rigidity and a high degree of intermolecular interaction, typically resulting in a higher melting point. There are three tertiary nitrogen atoms which may participate in hydrogen bonding and dipole-dipole interactions, but their effect is somewhat attenuated due to their tertiary nature, providing only a moderate boost. The molecule also contains an ester group (–COO–), which may participate in dipole-dipole interactions, increasing the melting point. Lastly, the presence of an aromatic ring generally raises the melting point due to π-π stacking interactions. Here are the estimated numeric contributions of each functional group to the melting point:
- Tricyclic core structure: +100 (due to rigidity and strong intermolecular forces)
- Tertiary nitrogen atoms: +15 (moderate increase because of decreased hydrogen bonding potential)
- Ester group: +20 (because of dipole-dipole interactions)
- Aromatic ring: +15 (due to π-π stacking interactions)
Taking the simplest hydrocarbon (methane) as a base with a melting point of -182 degrees Celsius for our baseline and adding the contributions, the estimated melting point of physostigmine would be approximately -32 (methane baseline) + 100 (tricyclic core) + 15 (nitrogen atoms) + 20 (ester group) + 15 (aromatic ring) = 118 degrees Celsius.
